 Business Briefs
																								 Mumbai, Oct. 8: Reserve Bank governor Y.V. Reddy today said the country is vulnerable to shocks arising out of volatility in global oil prices. But, he said, setting up a stabilisation fund was not justified under the given situation. There is no serious consideration of setting up a stabilisation or sovereign wealth fund, Reddy said. India imports 73 per cent of oil to meet its fuel needs and faces inflationary pressure on any sharp increase in global crude prices.																								 Mumbai, Oct. 8: Utkal Alumina International has become a 100 per cent subsidiary of Hindalco Industries. Hindalco has completed the acquisition of Alcan Incs entire shareholding in the Orissa-based firm.																								 New Delhi, Oct. 8: China Metallurgical Group Corporation has emerged as one of the bidders to build Essar Steels two-million-tonne steel plant in Vietnam, according to a report by the Metal Bulletin, which quoted a Vietnam Steel Corporation official. The proposed steel plant is a joint venture in which Essar will hold a 65 per cent stake.																								 Mumbai, Oct. 8: The Bank of India (BoI) has raised Rs 155 crore from bonds to meet credit requirements. The funds were raised through private placement of innovative perpetual debt instruments, the bank informed the Bombay Stock Exchange. The bonds, carrying a coupon rate of 10.40 per cent, will be listed on the NSE. 																								 New Delhi, Oct. 8: Fujitsu will increase its headcount in India to 2,500 from 1,500 in three years. India is a very important location for the company to help cater to increasing global client base efficiently. As our operations expand here, we expect to employ an additional 1,000 people by 2010, Fujitsu CEO John T. Rose said here.																								 London/New York, Oct. 8: Officials at French drug maker Sanofi-Aventis and Pfizer declined to comment on Monday on the market talk that Pfizer was looking to buy stakes from Sanofis major shareholders.
